"1300–Deceased","1305–Female":"1305–Deceased","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1411":"1411","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1351":"1351","1382":"1382","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","Yorksire, England":"England","Ripley, Yorkshire, England":"Ripley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gerstone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Garston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Garston","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English (Flintshire and Lancashire):","habitational name from Garston in Lancashire, a placename meaning ‘the great stone’."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Gerstone was born in 1325, in Ripley, Yorkshire, England, her father, John GERSTONE, was 25 and her mother, Mrs. John Gerstone, was 21. She married Sir John Rockley in 1351, in Ripley, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1325–":"1325–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1320–1406":"1320–1406","1354–1411":"1354–1411","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1305–Female":"1305–Surnud","1305":"